WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Hello everyone, this is Yihui, and today I'm going to talk about a project that I have been working for the past half year, which is called Bookdown, and it's an R package for writing books with R Markdown.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:47.000
So first I'd like to talk about some motivation behind this package. Actually I wanted to do this two years ago, but I managed to get some time earlier this year, so I started this project earlier this year, and there are some problems that I want to solve.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And I have been a student in the major of statistics for over 10 years, and I believe that there are some problems that we should solve for books.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:33.000
The first one is that books should have been much easier to write technically. Normally people use LaTeX or Word to write books, but these things are either not flexible or too complicated, and there are too many technical challenges, and today I will show you how easy it can be to write a book.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And the second problem is that I believe most of the books are just way too expensive, and my ideal price for the books are just like $10 or $20, and you know typically the books that you buy when you are a student, I mean the textbooks are typically like around $70 or $100 or sometimes even $200.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
That's just too expensive, and I believe we can cut some cost in the books.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:20.000
The third problem is that the books, especially the printed books, are never interactive, and the content is not rich enough.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:47.000
If you use Bookdown, you will see that you can have dynamic content in your books, which makes it much richer to read, and for example you can embed interactive HTML widgets or even interactive shiny apps right in the book, and when you read the book, you can just interact with these widgets or apps.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So you can just imagine that when you read a book on, for example, linear regression, you can just fit a linear regression by yourself as you read the book, or if you read a book on machine learning, you can just turn the parameters in your models and see the output directly.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:16.000
So that is just like a personalized book, just like personalized medicine.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:25.000
So you can have your own version of book, so it's very interactive, and the content can be very rich.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And the fourth problem is that typically books are very slow to iterate, and so after you publish your first edition of book, you often have to wait for several years to write the second edition, and I believe that's just way too slow, and it can be much quicker to iterate, and I will show you how.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:11.000
And the last problem is that the books are often written by one person or a limited number of authors, and the feedback that you get when you write a book is very limited as well.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:36.000
So typically your publisher will find some reviewers for you, it's like three anonymous reviewers, and you only get the feedback from them, and I firmly believe that you can attract a much larger number of contributors to your book, and you can get much, much more feedback on the book, and I will also show you how.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:05:05.000
So when you are thinking about writing a book, so you may open your LaTeX editor or Word to write a book, and when you want to buy a book, the book can be like $300, which is too expensive, and when you are considering writing another edition of the book, I guess you probably often look like this.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:18.000
You just simply give up, because there are many problems. For example, we need to solve these problems, we don't want these problems to happen over and over again.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:42.000
We need to end that. For example, if you are familiar with LaTeX, you should understand what I mean in this GIF. So if you work with LaTeX, sometimes LaTeX can be very fragile, even if you change only a little bit in your document, you can totally screw up your layout.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:51.000
Your figures and tables can float anywhere in the book, and it's just very distractive when you write the book.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And how about Word? I know many people use Word, and Word is good if you write a few paragraphs, and sometimes maybe after you write a few other paragraphs, and you feel very good. But if you write a long document, like a book or a very long report, eventually it will just blow up, like this.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:38.000
So we don't want you to be in that situation. So what I would recommend is that you can use Markdown. Markdown is a very simple language. I assume most of our attendees today are reasonably familiar with Markdown.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So basically, if you are able to write emails, you should be able to learn Markdown. And actually, I have a personal award, which is if you are not able to learn the basics of Markdown in 10 minutes, I will just award you $10.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So Markdown is very simple to write. It's just as simple as this. You just hop on the car and you're ready to go.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:31.000
Actually, because Markdown is so simple, of course there are some features for writing books that are missing in Markdown. Actually, the original Markdown was designed for writing HTML content, and it was very simple.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:47.000
But we have developed a package called rMarkdown, which added two powerful components to Markdown and makes it suitable for writing articles and books.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:08:04.000
And these two components are Pandoc and R. So first, we added R to Markdown, which means we can mix R code with your Markdown text. So you can embed your computing right into your book.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So when you write a book or an article, you can just embed R code chunks there and you click a button and the R code chunks will just be executed. And you will get the output and you don't have to run the code separately and copy and paste the results.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:38.000
So we added R, which means you can do statistical computing, data analysis, data visualization in your document. So that's one source of force in Markdown.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:09:01.000
And the other component is Pandoc. And Pandoc is a very powerful tool for converting documents. And it can convert Markdown documents to many other formats, for example, to HTML or to LaTeX PDF or to ebooks and even Word documents and presentations.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:15.000
So it's another powerful tool. So with R and Pandoc, Markdown can be as powerful as this. So it has a lot of force.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:35.000
So that's R Markdown. And the story has not ended there. So now we have Bookdown. And just one sentence summary of Bookdown. It's a tool. It's a very simple tool that makes you look awesome.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Because when you write a book, you know, when you tell other people, oh, I wrote a book, and of course you look very awesome. So Bookdown is just that simple tool behind you that makes you look awesome.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:10:10.000
So you can write a book with very simple tools. And so I'm just going to show you some demos using Bookdown. Before that, I want to briefly explain the basic structure of books.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So when you write a book or a long report, you often do not want to write everything in one single R Markdown document. Instead, you have multiple R Markdown documents. And one R Markdown document is just one RMD file.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So you have multiple RMD files. Typically, each RMD file is a chapter. So you have multiple chapters, and Bookdown can convert these multiple chapters into a book. And the output format can be like PDF or HTML or EPUB. EPUB is a format for ebooks.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:21.000
And in Bookdown, I also extended some Markdown features. For example, as I said, the original Markdown was very simple. And in Pandocs, Markdown is more powerful, but it still lacks some common features, especially for academic writing, for example.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:38.000
It currently does not have the feature of numbering your figures and tables or cross-reference your figures and tables. And I added this feature in Bookdown, and I will show you examples later.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:12:00.000
You can also embed interactive content, like videos or HTML widgets or Shiny applications in your book. And you may ask, when the output is not HTML, for example, if it's PDF or EPUB, how can these HTML widgets or Shiny apps work?

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:20.000
And that would be a very good question, and the answer is that if the output format is not HTML, Bookdown will just automatically take screenshots of HTML widgets and Shiny apps and embed a static screenshot in your book.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:40.000
But if your reader wants to know more about these interactive widgets, they either go to the HTML output of your book or go to the URL of the Shiny apps to interact with this interactive content.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:13:03.000
You can have different styles in the output as well, and the style that I personally like very much is a style called Gitbook style, and some people might be familiar with this.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:13.000
So this style was actually borrowed from another open source project called Gitbook, so you can know more about that from Gitbook.com.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:20.000
And we borrowed the style from them, but we replaced the internal Markdown renderer with RMarkdown.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:31.000
So basically that means we are using Pandoc to render the book instead of their simple Markdown renderer.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:53.000
And the Gitbook style is also very responsive in terms of that when you read the book on smaller devices like on your phone, the layout will just automatically adjust to the smaller devices.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And there are also different themes like lighter themes or darker themes, and I will show you these themes later.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And also you can click an edit button to edit the RMarkdown source document, and there are other buttons on the toolbar.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:20.000
And let me just quickly show you the example.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:28.000
So the source document for this example is actually on GitHub.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
It's under RStudio's account.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
It's called bookdown-demo.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:45.000
So if you are interested in trying that out right now, you can just go to this GitHub repository.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:50.000
So this is just a minimal bookdown demo.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:15:05.000
So as I said, a book consists of multiple RMD files, like I have an index RMD that is the first chapter or the homepage of your book.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And then you have like 01, 02, 03 up to 06, and these are RMarkdown chapters.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So you have these chapters.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:24.000
As this is only a minimal example, these chapters are just pretty much like one sentence.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
So you have multiple RMD files.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And if you have installed bookdown, actually I uploaded bookdown to CRAN just last night.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:41.000
So you might be able to install bookdown from CRAN.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:51.000
If it's not in your CRAN mirror yet, you can just install from GitHub using DevTools.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:02.000
You can use DevTools, install GitHub, RStudio, bookdown.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
So that's how you can install the package.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:12.000
Once it's installed, you will be able to compile these RMD files into a book.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:19.000
So the minimal configuration is this.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:28.000
So in the index.rmd, you have a site option, which is bookdown, bookdown site.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:33.000
Then the output option, which is bookdown, colon, colon, Gitbook.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:39.000
Gitbook is just one of the output formats in bookdown.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:46.000
So let's just take a look at the Gitbook style first.

