So here's an edit button.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:10.000
And this edit button does not mean you edit the R Markdown source locally.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.000
This button is there for your potential contributors.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:23.000
So when your reader clicks this button, it will take you to GitHub.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.000
As I said, this repository is on GitHub.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:33.000
When your reader clicks this button, it will take you to the R Markdown source document on GitHub.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:42.000
For example, it will be very helpful if your reader finds a typo in your book.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:53.000
And he or she can just fix that typo and commit that change on GitHub and send you a pull request.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:00.000
In case you are not familiar with pull requests, let me just show you an example of pull requests.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:11.000
So basically a pull request is that you can fork other people's GitHub repository to your own account

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:16.000
and make some changes and then send the changes back to the original repository.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:24.000
So here is the repository of the book R for Data Science by Hadley and Garrett.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:29.000
And you can see many people have contributed to that book.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:41.000
And I guess the most common pull request is the ones that fix the fixed typos.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:46.000
And you can see many of the pull requests have been merged.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:50.000
Let me show you how the changes look like.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:58.000
So basically when you read a book, if you find some typos, you can just click that edit button and make these changes

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:02.000
and submit these changes back to the original repository.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:16.000
And when the author sees your changes, he can just click a button called a merge pull request to merge your changes back into the main repository.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:30.000
So this little edit button, I believe it will be very helpful if you put your book in a public place.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:39.000
We have a website called bookdown.org that allows you to host your book online for free.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:45.000
And when other people read your book and find some problems or they want to make suggestions,

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:50.000
they can just hit this edit button and it will take you to the R Markdown source.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:56.000
And you can make whatever changes you want and send the changes back to the authors.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:06.000
So that would be a very interesting way to provide feedback or help the authors write their books.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:11.000
So that is what I meant in the beginning.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:22.000
The books are often written by a small number of authors, but they should attract attention from many, many other readers.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.000
And these readers can contribute to your book.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:33.000
And so the last button on the left on the toolbar is a download button.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:45.000
So as I said, the Git book style is basically a series of HTML pages and you can download the book in other formats, for example, PDF and EPUB.

