So let's go back to the build tab again.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:59.000
So you can build this book using the Git book format.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:08.000
You can also create a PDF book to build the same R Markdown documents into a PDF document.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:26.000
So basically, Bookdown will just call the PDF book format and LaTeX to compile these R Markdown files into a book like this.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:29.000
You can see this is a PDF book.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
We have a table of contents.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:34.000
We have different chapters.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:41.000
We can have floating figures and tables in the book.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:45.000
So that's the PDF output.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:50.000
And we also have the EPUB ebook.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.000
We can render the book to EPUB.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:25:00.000
And since I'm using Mac, it opened the ebook in iBooks.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:06.000
So still the same content, different output formats.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:21.000
And another cool thing about this multiple output format is that pretty much all the features will work in all the output formats.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:36.000
For example, when you have cross-references of chapters or figures and tables, all these cross-references will work in EPUB and HTML and PDF.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:43.000
So you don't have to worry too much about your possible output format.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:48.000
So that's the PDF and EPUB output.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And finally, on the Gitbook toolbar on the right, there's a share button.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:05.000
So you can click these buttons to share the link of your book on your social network media like Facebook or Twitter.

