00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:51.000
Let me just walk you through some features that I think are very cool.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:57.000
So there's basic Markdown syntax in chapter 2.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:01.000
And I'm not going to repeat these features.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:09.000
And one thing I want to mention is that you should be able to write math expressions in your book.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:12.000
So you can see some math equations there.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:17.000
So that's just the LaTeX syntax.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:24.000
Basically, you just write your math expressions in a pair of dollar signs.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:36.000
So talking about math, there is actually a feature in Bookdown, which is there is an add-in.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:41.000
So if you use Bookdown, there is an add-in called input LaTeX math.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:45.000
You can get that from the RStudio toolbar.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:54.000
And this add-in is to help you write your math content in a visual way.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:34:03.000
So, you know, personally, I really hate reading a full screen of backslashes, especially when I type the math.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:18.000
You know, it's very easy to screw up the math content if you cannot see the math expressions visually.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:26.000
So this RStudio add-in can help you type the math expressions.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:31.000
And it also shows you the LaTeX source of the math content.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:41.000
So when you are done, you can click done, and you will see the math equation in your RMarkdown source document.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:48.000
And you just add a pair of dollar signs, and there will be a math equation there.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:51.000
So that's the math.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:58.000
And you can embed R code chunks. You should be very familiar with that.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:03.000
You can number figures and tables and cross-references.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:06.000
And you can also have some custom blocks.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:14.000
Like sometimes you may want to write some notes or warnings or information in your book.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
So you can use these custom blocks.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:25.000
I'm not going to show you the detailed syntax, but I just want to let you know that this is a possibility.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:29.000
And I mentioned HTML widgets and Shiny apps.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:39.000
So when the output format is HTML, you will see the HTML widgets live in your book.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:55.000
For example, I'm using an HTML widget package called DT here, which can convert your data frames and matrices into a table like this in your book.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:36:01.000
So basically, you can print a data frame in multiple pages.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:04.000
You can sort the table interactively.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:07.000
You can search in the table.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:12.000
So there are many, many other HTML widgets packages that you can use.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.000
And this is just one of the examples.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:20.000
And also for Shiny apps.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:31.000
So when your reader comes to your book and they can just interact with certain content in your book.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:35.000
For example, I embedded a Shiny app here.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:38.000
The app has been published to Shinyapps.io.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:45.000
So I just include that URL of the app in the book.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:48.000
So now this is actually live.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.000
So you can zoom in the map.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:54.000
You can interact with the map.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:01.000
You can see different tabs in this Shiny application.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:08.000
You can see the source data or other tabs.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:15.000
So that's how you can interact with Shiny apps in the book.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:21.000
And when the output format is not HTML, this will just be a screenshot.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:31.000
Let me talk a little bit about customization.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:37.000
So actually these output formats are highly customizable.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:43.000
I just want to show you one simple example.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:50.000
Let's just use LaTeX output as an example.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:03.000
I'm not sure how many people have used a LaTeX document class called ComaScript.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:11.000
And that LaTeX document class is called SRCbook.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:15.000
And you may need to install a LaTeX package.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:22.000
But anyway, I just want to show you how you can change the style of the output.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:25.000
Just using some simple options.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
Oops.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:31.000
Oh, sorry. It's not SRC. It's SCR.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:37.000
Let's build this book to PDF again.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:48.000
So it will be using ComaScript to typeset your book.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:52.000
So you can see now the style is different.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:39:02.000
And just with a very simple change, you can totally change the appearance of your book.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:10.000
And of course there are a lot of other things that you can customize.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:19.000
For example, for the Gitbook style, you can choose which buttons to show there.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:24.000
For example, you may disable this sharing button.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:29.000
And you can hide this download button.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:36.000
Or set the font size or font family in advance.

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:40.000
There are many, many options for you to customize the book.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:56.000
Okay, one last thing I want to mention about Bookdown is that there's a function called PublishBook.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:09.000
So after you have compiled your book, you can call this PublishBook function to publish your book to this website, bookdown.org.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:13.000
So currently it's free for you to host your book.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:20.000
And just one simple call of this function and your book will show up here.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:33.000
So now we have a number of books like the book for Bookdown and R for Data Science, Efficient R Programming, R Programming for Data Science, and a lot of other books.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:40.000
And if you want to learn from other people's examples, you can start from here.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:50.000
And there are detailed instructions on how you can get started with RStudio and bookdown.org.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:41:04.000
Okay.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:21.000
Oh, another thing I should have emphasized is that since you have multiple chapters, and just to save you some time compiling the book,

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:31.000
the default behavior of clicking the Net button on the RStudio toolbar is only to preview the current chapter.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:39.000
So that means if you are in this chapter and you click the Net button, it will only compile this chapter.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:48.000
And sometimes this can be confusing because if you only compile this chapter, other chapters may or may not work.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.000
They may not have been compiled.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:59.000
So in that case, you shouldn't navigate to other chapters because their content may not be correct.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:05.000
So this Net button is only for preview purposes.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:09.000
So if you click this button, it only compiles this single chapter.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:16.000
So that may save you some time if you have some time consuming computation in other chapters.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:22.000
If you want to compile the whole book, always use the Build button here.

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:25.000
This will compile all the chapters.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:35.000
So just one thing to notice about the RStudio IDE.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:38.000
Yeah, that's pretty much what I have today.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:48.000
And if you go back and try out the bookdown package by yourself, you may run into certain issues that you don't understand.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:57.000
And just don't worry because I just released the first version of bookdown to CRAN yesterday.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:06.000
So I will not be surprised if there are still some bugs or issues.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:14.000
So if you run into these issues, please just file them to the GitHub repository.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:19.000
Or you can ask questions on Stack Overflow with the tag bookdown.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:30.000
And lastly, if you can't remember all the things I talked about today, you can just go back and check out the website bookdown.org.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:44.000
And if you want to send me any feedback, you can either let me know on Twitter or GitHub or find my email on my homepage.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:47.000
Or you can contact RStudio.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:52.000
I want to thank you very much for being here.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:58.000
One person asked, how does one reorder the chapters?

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:00.000
Okay, that's a very good question.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:03.000
Alright, yeah, that's a very good question.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:10.000
So you have multiple RMD files here and the default order is just the natural order.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:15.000
That's why I named these RMD files as 010203.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:25.000
If you want to reorder these chapters, there is a configuration file called bookdown.yaml.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:33.000
So there you can have an option named RMD files.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:37.000
It's this RMD files option.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:49.000
So you basically provide your own order of these RMD files using this RMD files option in the configuration file underscore bookdown.yaml.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:57.000
Someone asked, can cross references be forward references?

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.000
And the answer is yes.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:05.000
It doesn't matter where your figures or tables are.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:13.000
You can simply use the chunk label with the syntax that I mentioned, the backslash at ref.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:21.000
You may generate a figure later in the chapter and refer to it earlier in the chapter.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:27.000
And the next one is, can you use Python with bookdown?

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.000
And the answer is also yes.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:39.000
So to use Python, instead of 3 backticks with R, you just use 3 backticks Python.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:49.000
Actually this is not perfect at the moment and we will improve this in the future.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:46:03.000
So yeah, actually besides Python you can use many many other types of languages like C++, you can use RCMP, you can use C code, you can use Fortran.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:07.000
And also if you are familiar with Bash, you can use Bash.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:12.000
So all these features come from Nitter actually.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:27.000
Alright, the next question is regarding math, how to align and label equations in R Markdown or Bookdown?

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:30.000
How to align and label equations?

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:36.000
I believe you can use the align environment.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:49.000
So even if this is converted to non-LaTeX output, the equations should be preserved.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
For example, for HTML output.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:47:03.000
I'm not sure if I'm typing the correct syntax here, but I think the align environment is in LaTeX and you can still use that for HTML output as well.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:12.000
And for equation labels, you can just use the syntax backslash label.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:21.000
Actually this does not work very well in terms of the HTML output.

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:28.000
If you label an equation, you can only refer to it in the current chapter.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:32.000
You cannot refer to an equation in another chapter.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:48.000
The next question is, is the syntax backslash at ref generic to R Markdown or only available in Bookdown?

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:51.000
And the answer is, it's only available in Bookdown.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:59.000
Actually there's one thing I forgot to mention.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:10.000
If you don't want to use Bookdown, but you want the feature of numbering figures and tables and cross-references,

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:35.000
you can actually leave out this cite option, but you set the output format to be HTML document 2 or PDF document 2 or Word document 2.

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:46.000
So these formats are designed specifically for the feature of numbering and cross-referencing figures and tables.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:56.000
So these output formats, for example, the Word document 2 format is almost the same as the Word document format in R Markdown,

00:48:56.000 --> 00:49:02.000
but it just added the feature of cross-references and the numbering figures.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:14.000
The next question is, is Tufti book format supported?

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:19.000
And I'm very glad that you guys are asking fantastic questions.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:23.000
And the answer is yes, Tufti book is supported.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:47.000
For example, if you want the HTML output for Tufti books, you can just use the Tufti HTML book format.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:55.000
If you want PDF, I believe it's simply handout 2 or book 2.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
Yeah, so you can use Tufti.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:08.000
Next question is, is Bookdown a replacement of Gitbook or a competitor?

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:21.000
I'm not sure how to answer that, but the only thing I can tell you is that Gitbook is one of the output formats in Bookdown,

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:33.000
and the major difference between Gitbook.com and Bookdown is that the Markdown renderer is different.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:47.000
So we use Pandoc to render Markdown documents, and they use, I don't remember, they use their own or a simpler Markdown renderer.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:51.000
So I believe there are many features that are missing there.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:58.000
For example, they definitely don't have the feature of numbering figures or writing bibliography.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:16.000
Next question is, can you comment on differences between this approach and using read-down RMD template from RMD formats package?

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:32.000
Yeah, I saw read-down package, read-down format a while ago, but I haven't tried that, and it looks very attractive to me.

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:41.000
But I need to read more about it to tell you the exact differences.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:50.000
Next question, is there a complete list of YAML options documented somewhere?

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:59.000
And the answer is yes, it's documented in the Bookdown documentation in section number 1.4.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
And let me pick a shorter question.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:17.000
What is the possibility of using this in conjunction with something like IEEE journal data templates so that we can write conference and journal articles?

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:19.000
That's also a very good question.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:30.000
And the answer is that instead of using Bookdown, there's a package called Articles, also in the RStudio repository called Articles.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:37.000
And there are several examples of using RMD for journal articles.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:48.000
Probably I can show you a very quick example of writing a paper for journal of statistical software.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:56.000
Let's create a new document under Documents.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:06.000
So this is just an RMD document, and it's using the Articles package to compile this document.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:10.000
And now you can see you have a journal article.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:21.000
And the only thing you want to do is that you have to write a LaTeX template.

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:26.000
And as I said, there are many examples here.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:34.000
So you can probably study these templates and then use the IEEE LaTeX style.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:39.000
And then you can combine RMD with these journal styles.

